    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Kean University moved to the historic Livingston‑Kean Estate in 1958, making the campus home to Liberty Hall, the James Townley House, and Kean Hall.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kean_University"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The campus’s Kean Hall, built in 1912, once housed Senator Hamilton Fish Kean’s library and served as a political meeting place.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        29
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kean_University"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "In 1973 the institution was renamed Kean College of New Jersey, and it earned full university status in 1997.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kean_University"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Kean University hosts the Holocaust Resource Center, the NJ STEM Center, and the Human Rights Institute, making it a hub for research on social justice.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kean_University"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "The campus’s majestic Kean Hall, described as castle‑like, is a popular spot for stage productions and film series.",
